##The old man healed but refused to leave the hospital? Wang Zhen, head of the shanghai-hubei psychological medical team, explains "the psychological wounds of the Wuhan People" 

Micro Signal Xinminzhoukan

Function description, depth and angle —— this is what we can do.

The psychological team came to Wuhan more than a month after the outbreak, and it was a good time. We hoped that during the stress period when the outbreak was not over, we could help him to ease his anxiety so as not to cause long-term effects.
Reporter | Huang Qi

More than a month after the outbreak of new crown pneumonia in Wuhan, a psychological medical team with psychiatrists as its main members, organized by the National Health Commission, rushed to Wuhan from all over the country. The shanghai-hubei psychological medical team is one of the first psychological medical teams to arrive in Wuhan. The 50 members of the team come from Shanghai Mental Health Center and Shanghai District Mental Health Centers. On February 21, the shanghai-hubei psychological medical team arrived in Wuhan and has already started work in six new pneumonia hospitals and four shelter hospitals.
This is the first time that China has organized psychological medical teams on a large scale to carry out psychological intervention work in key areas of the epidemic. Shanghai, Hunan, Sichuan and other provinces and cities have sent eight psychological medical teams on a large scale, a total of 300 people work with clinicians in various medical institutions in Wuhan to provide services for patients, as well as mental health care for medical staff.
Yesterday (March 1) , Shanghai to Hubei Psychological medical team leader, vice president of the Shanghai Mental Health Center accepted the "Xinmin Weekly" interview. Wang Zhen said the shanghai-hubei medical team was familiar with the situation immediately after arriving in Wuhan, and coordinated with the local medical institutions, has entered the ward on February 26 to carry out work.
Wang Zhen talks to a patient in the ward of Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital

According to Wang Zhen, there are some people who have psychological problems of varying degrees, whether they are seriously ill in a designated hospital or mildly ill in a shelter hospital. It is a very timely and appropriate measure to carry out psychological intervention in an orderly and scientific manner at the point when the epidemic has progressed to more than one month. After a few days of mapping, Wang Zhen found that the sick elderly and sick children and children who had lost loved ones in the epidemic were the groups he was most concerned about, and that future focused interventions and long term follow up were needed for these groups.

Early "help" , now "save the heart. "

"Xinmin Weekly" : You work in Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital, the main admission of critically ill patients, you see patients in the current state of mind?
Wang Zhen: Members of the mental health team who work at the designated intake hospital serve patients primarily in the form of liaison consultations, in other words, clinicians find that some patients may have psychological problems, they'll send us to a specialist for tests and diagnostics.
Yesterday we consulted three patients, one of whom was elderly and had already developed symptoms of depression, and the initial assessment was moderate depression.
The old man's wife died many years ago, before living alone, take care of themselves without much problem. After being admitted to Jinyintan Hospital, we were in charge of the Hubei Medical Team in Shanghai. He recovered quickly from the treatment, but his mental state has not been so good. When not cured, he often clamored to be discharged from the hospital, in fact, it is a manifestation of anxiety and fear. Now that he was well enough to leave the hospital, he was determined not to leave. The clinician said that when he was told to leave the hospital, he refused to speak to the doctor, was very upset and even had the idea of committing suicide.
We went into the hospital room to talk to him at the bedside. He wouldn't talk at first, but then he finally said it. His biggest fear was that he wouldn't be welcome home.
The old man is very eager to go home, but the children may tell him, for fear that he can not go back to life, everyone in isolation, the home is unable to take care of him.
He didn't want to leave because he was worried. Plus the hospital staff to take good care of him, this contrast, the heart will be very sad, feel oneself can not go home, slowly generate some negative thoughts.
Knowing what he was thinking, we started with some cognitive counseling, telling him that the community had a life plan for him in isolation after he left the hospital. Then guide him to understand his children's original intention is not to dislike him, teach him how to communicate with his children. And Guide him through his grief.
After nearly half an hour of psychological counseling, the old man's mood has calmed down, but because his depressive symptoms are still more obvious, we also gave him medication. We don't have the antidepressants we need, and just before you called me, I was coordinating a transfer to the hospital with the help of the Wuhan Mental Health Center.
Xinmin Weekly: The other two patients had less symptoms, right?
Wang Zhen: Yes. There was a middle-aged patient who had been cured of pneumonia and had been able to walk around the ward, doing well in every way. One day the doctor told him he could leave the hospital, and the next day he couldn't get out of bed. The clinician knew that he was a physical response to psychological symptoms, but did not know how to deal with them.
The patient said he was worried: What if I get sick again and there is no doctor to help me? What if I'm not really good? He felt safe in the hospital. It wasn't safe to go home.
We went in, we gave him some counseling, we gave him some relaxation exercises, and he's basically fine since we talked.
Three psychiatrists from Shanghai Mental Health Center are in Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital

Xinmin Weekly: We imagine that we would be very happy to be out of the hospital. I didn't know discharge patients were prone to mental health problems.
Wang Zhen: When the disease is serious, there is no time to take into account the psychological feelings, then life saving, and when the patient's physical disease eased, the psychological symptoms showed up. Our psychological medical team came to Wuhan more than a month after the outbreak. It was a good time. We hoped to help him ease his anxiety during the stress period when the epidemic was not over, so as not to cause long-term effects. Because the early main task is to save the patient, the psychologist in the "life-saving" section is not too much use, or even make trouble. In the middle and late stages of the epidemic, it is important for the National Health Commission to send out psychological medical teams in time.

Children and the elderly, the weak in the epidemic
Xinmin Weekly: What other psychological problems are unique among patients?
Wang Zhen: The hospital where several of my colleagues work in the Shanghai psychiatric team, has patients who have been transferred from nursing homes, some of whom have Alzheimer's disease, or early Alzheimer's disease.
Some of these patients can not not not cooperate with treatment, will multiply the workload of health care workers, may health care workers to take care of this patient, the other seven or eight patients can not cope. We received a consultation request, through drug treatment and part of the support of emotional counseling, to help patients better with the treatment. For example, for those with sleep reversal Alzheimer's who have behavioral disorders during the night, we can give a sedative that improves both behavior and sleep, says antipsychotic, MD, a sleep researcher at the University of California, San Diego.
Xinmin Weekly: What other groups do you think need special attention?
Wang Zhen: Son! This is a group that I think needs special attention. A team of colleagues from the Shanghai team worked at the Wuhan Children's Hospital, which treated some of the children. My biggest concern is their future.
Many of the cases were family-acquired. Some of these children may have lost their parents to the disease. Their psychological problems require our attention.
We're still running a screen, trying to get a ballpark figure on each kid. This screening is not easy to do, because some children may not know the family situation, adults and children in different places for treatment.
Xinmin Weekly: There have also been a lot of sad news stories recently, such as a child living with his grandfather, who had been dead for two or three days when a member of the community knocked on his door. There was another girl, chasing the hearse, calling out for her mother. These kids, are they GONNA be traumatized?
Wang Zhen: Yes. At present our work is still limited to medical institutions, Wuhan community because of the outbreak of direct psychological harm children, we can not take into account, hope that the community attention to them.
"Chronic Stress Response" of infectious disease epidemic situation is different from earthquake

Xinmin Weekly: We saw the square dancing in the shelter hospital. Is the mental health of the patients with mild illness better?
Wang Zhen: our Shanghai team of 50 doctors was divided into 10 teams, and we were assigned to 10 hospitals, six of which were designated hospitals, four of which were shelter hospitals, and each team had five doctors.
The situation in a shelter hospital is very different from that in a designated hospital. There are many people in the shelter hospital, many thousands of them. The common psychological problem of the patients in the shelter hospital is anxiety. The main cause of anxiety, apart from the disease itself, is the fear of uncertainty about the future. For example, they have to go into quarantine after going out of the cabin. They worry about the living arrangement there. They also worry about whether they will be discriminated against or ostracized when they return home.
Another common symptom is insomnia. On the one hand, the reason for insomnia is not adapted to the environment of the Shelter Hospital, on the other hand, there are also concerns about the epidemic, because the whole epidemic has not ended, psychological stress is still there. Depression is relatively rare in a shelter hospital, but if anxiety is not alleviated, the effects can be severe and depression can occur in some people over a long period of time.
Overall, about 50% of patients who actively express their emotional problems to health care professionals need some psychological intervention, but their psychological problems are relatively mild, we can take a variety of forms of intervention.
Fifty specialists from the Shanghai Mental Health Center and the Shanghai District Mental Health Center form the Shanghai Aid Hubei Medical Team

Xinmin Weekly: What psychological interventions are available to psychologists in a shelter hospital?
Wang Zhen: You can see the patients dancing in the square. In fact, after I came here, I also had some exchanges with the doctors on the front line. The doctors think that square dancing is not suitable for everyone, i wouldn't go dancing in a public square. Do breathing exercise is better, the amount of exercise is not large, and can adjust the breathing function, or the right amount of activities is better.
The overall mental health of the patients in the shelter hospital is relatively good, which has an important relationship with the overall coordination and management of the shelter hospital as well as logistical support in place. For example, the food supply for the patients is very good, but the more important reason is that the doctors and nurses involved in the shelter work are very professional and care for the patients, and the harmonious doctor-patient relationship helps to reduce the ill effects of the disease on the patients.
For patients who need psychological intervention, we have taken a variety of psychological intervention measures. For example, the Shelter Hospital has a broadcasting system, we are busy these two days recording a variety of audio programs to provide patients with some mental health knowledge, psychological protection.
Another important task is to conduct psychological screening of patients. The medical team, in cooperation with Shanghai Jiaotong University, built an assessment system. We put qr codes on our shelter hospitals, and on our doctor's protective clothing. Patients scan the codes and do self-help psychological assessments, the patient sees the results for himself and comes to the psychologist. Doctors in the background can also see the results of the survey, doctors if the situation is more serious patients, can take the initiative to contact patients for timely intervention. We'll know more about the patient when we have a lot of patient studies.

We have also done a lot of mental health information, ready to take to the shelter hospital to send to patients, but also use wechat tweets, so that patients understand more psychological knowledge and self-help methods.
In Wuhan, Wang Zhen held an online meeting with the Shanghai Jiaotong University research team to develop tools for psychological assessment and treatment of patients and health care workers affected by the outbreak

Xinmin Weekly: How are the psychological problems of patients in infectious disease epidemics different from disasters like earthquakes, fires and so on?
Wang Zhen: Infectious Diseases are not like earthquakes. Earthquakes and fires are one time things. Infectious Diseases last a long time, and a lot of people have psychological problems because of chronic stress.
Whether it's a fire or an earthquake, it's confined to a specific area. Even a quake as big as the Wenchuan County quake is only in Sichuan Province, and the rest of the country is unlikely to be affected. Infectious diseases are different, especially this one, which is spreading very fast, and everyone is potentially at risk, so it's very easy to create a panic in the whole society, even if you don't have an infected person around you, you're in a panic because you don't know if it's going to happen to you tomorrow.
A real threat can cause a dramatic rise in anxiety levels, which, unlike earthquakes and fires, do not affect the same number of people. In areas where the epidemic is severe, people like these in Wuhan may have post traumatic stress disorder, especially if they have a disease of their own that has a lingering effect, or if a family member has died, or those who have witnessed the death of a relative, or someone close to them, may develop the disease later.
But we also found that traditional Chinese culture has a strong protective effect on our mental health, so the rate of true PTSD later in life may be lower than reported in the West. In this kind of group crisis, Chinese people's psychological resilience seems to be stronger, for example, the traditional belief that "if you survive a disaster, you will be blessed later" has its very positive significance in the face of a big disaster, to protect our mental health.
Another must be emphasized is the strong response mechanisms adopted by our countries and governments, the strong mobilization and coordination capacity in the face of the epidemic, which can invisibly enhance people's confidence and sense of security.
Xinmin Weekly: Do you think the intervention of psychological intervention in the NCP epidemic is a big improvement over the past?
Wang Zhen: After the 2008 earthquake in Wenchuan County, there were a lot of psychologists and counselors who volunteered to work in the disaster area. Their wish is good, but because the psychological intervention work organization is quite chaotic, some people actually bring the disaster victims the second trauma. There are some psychological counselors lack of professional ability, to the scene will also bring some trouble.
After the Wenchuan County earthquake and other disasters, the field of psychological intervention to sum up the experience and lessons, now all aspects of the importance of psychological intervention, organizational capacity and professionalism than in those years much progress.
Xinmin Weekly: In these years of major disasters and infectious diseases, more and more psychologists are being seen. What are the results of your work?
Wang Zhen: In my memory, the first time Shanghai had a large scale psychological intervention was after the 1115 fire. Less than 24 hours after the fire, the psychological intervention team from the Shanghai Mental Health Center had already entered the scene. We did psychological screening and counseling for people who were affected by the disaster. It was a very successful psychological crisis intervention. These experiences for the follow-up of a variety of emergencies in the psychological intervention work, played a good role in the model. Later our psychological medical team also participated in the Bund stampede accident, many field explosion accident, shipwreck accident, etc. , the effect is better.
If the epidemic situation of infectious disease intervention, in 2003, when the Shanghai Mental Health Center Professor Xu Yifeng and Professor Huang Jizhong went to the treatment of SARS patients in the Shanghai Public Health Center work. In those days, there were no video phones, and unlike today, when everyone had a cell phone, doctors had to write instructions on cardboard through a window. It was our first official attempt at a psychological intervention. At the end of last year, when the plague struck Inner Mongolia, Shanghai also sent in psychologists.
After 2003, after several major events, the emergency system of psychological crisis intervention has been gradually established in China. With the development of society, Mental Health System, mental emergency mechanism gradually mature, a variety of plans gradually complete, once the outbreak, the emergency system on the start. As soon as the Wuhan epidemic broke out, the Shanghai Mental Health Center was already making preparations. Especially after we saw that a psychiatric hospital in Wuhan had infected medical staff, we were ready to take over some of the wards if necessary, but later our Wuhan colleague was very hard but brave to come through.
"Xinmin Weekly" : The psychological medical team to Wuhan also has a task is to ensure the psychological health of medical staff, at present you think the situation of medical staff?
Wang Zhen: these days we are in contact with more than the Shanghai Medical Team in Hubei Medical Staff, the overall situation is not bad, the more common problem is mainly insomnia.
There are several reasons for insomnia: First of all, many of our front-line nurses are senior and many of them are head nurses. They don't have to work shifts in their normal jobs. After arriving in Wuhan, they are scheduled according to ordinary nurses, difficulty adjusting your body clock can cause insomnia. In addition, the medical staff working in the ICU are under psychological and physical pressure. The patients are very sick. The medical staff often have to face such events as death due to ineffective treatment, which has a great impact on their psychology, this can cause mood swings, including anxiety, which is also an important cause of insomnia.
After we came here this time, we encountered some insomnia, anxiety of the medical staff, are doing the corresponding treatment. I think it will get better in the future, but if the treatment work lasts too long, homesickness is also a factor affecting the psychological state of the medical staff. Many of them have been in Wuhan for more than a month and are looking forward to going home. Moreover, on the one hand, we want to go home, want to rest, on the one hand, our medical staff are very dedicated, is very active to come to Wuhan to participate in the treatment, they also want to do the immediate work well, then there will be internal contradictions and conflicts.
Although I am cautiously optimistic, I am also worried that some medical staff are not willing to speak their minds, afraid that others will think that they are vulnerable, afraid of being misunderstood by others, so I will do more detailed work next, screen for those who don't reveal their true thoughts and emotions.

The psychological team came to Wuhan more than a month after the outbreak, and it was a good time. We hoped that during the stress period when the outbreak was not over, we could help him to ease his anxiety so as not to cause long-term effects.

"Xinmin Weekly" : The psychological medical team to Wuhan also has a task is to ensure the psychological health of medical staff, at present you think the situation of medical staff?
Wang Zhen: these days we are in contact with more than the Shanghai Medical Team in Hubei Medical Staff, the overall situation is not bad, the more common problem is mainly insomnia.
There are several reasons for insomnia: First of all, many of our front-line nurses are senior and many of them are head nurses. They don't have to work shifts in their normal jobs. After arriving in Wuhan, they are scheduled according to ordinary nurses, difficulty adjusting your body clock can cause insomnia. In addition, the medical staff working in the ICU are under psychological and physical pressure. The patients are very sick. The medical staff often have to face such events as death due to ineffective treatment, which has a great impact on their psychology, this can cause mood swings, including anxiety, which is also an important cause of insomnia.
After we came here this time, we encountered some insomnia, anxiety of the medical staff, are doing the corresponding treatment. I think it will get better in the future, but if the treatment work lasts too long, homesickness is also a factor affecting the psychological state of the medical staff. Many of them have been in Wuhan for more than a month and are looking forward to going home. Moreover, on the one hand, we want to go home, want to rest, on the one hand, our medical staff are very dedicated, is very active to come to Wuhan to participate in the treatment, they also want to do the immediate work well, then there will be internal contradictions and conflicts.
Although I am cautiously optimistic, I am also worried that some medical staff are not willing to speak their minds, afraid that others will think that they are vulnerable, afraid of being misunderstood by others, so I will do more detailed work next, screen for those who don't reveal their true thoughts and emotions.

Reporter | Huang Qi

More than a month after the outbreak of new crown pneumonia in Wuhan, a psychological medical team with psychiatrists as its main members, organized by the National Health Commission, rushed to Wuhan from all over the country. The shanghai-hubei psychological medical team is one of the first psychological medical teams to arrive in Wuhan. The 50 members of the team come from Shanghai Mental Health Center and Shanghai District Mental Health Centers. On February 21, the shanghai-hubei psychological medical team arrived in Wuhan and has already started work in six new pneumonia hospitals and four shelter hospitals.

This is the first time that China has organized psychological medical teams on a large scale to carry out psychological intervention work in key areas of the epidemic. Shanghai, Hunan, Sichuan and other provinces and cities have sent eight psychological medical teams on a large scale, a total of 300 people work with clinicians in various medical institutions in Wuhan to provide services for patients, as well as mental health care for medical staff.

Yesterday (March 1) , Shanghai to Hubei Psychological medical team leader, vice president of the Shanghai Mental Health Center accepted the "Xinmin Weekly" interview. Wang Zhen said the shanghai-hubei medical team was familiar with the situation immediately after arriving in Wuhan, and coordinated with the local medical institutions, has entered the ward on February 26 to carry out work.

Wang Zhen talks to a patient in the ward of Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital

According to Wang Zhen, there are some people who have psychological problems of varying degrees, whether they are seriously ill in a designated hospital or mildly ill in a shelter hospital. It is a very timely and appropriate measure to carry out psychological intervention in an orderly and scientific manner at the point when the epidemic has progressed to more than one month. After a few days of mapping, Wang Zhen found that the sick elderly and sick children and children who had lost loved ones in the epidemic were the groups he was most concerned about, and that future focused interventions and long term follow up were needed for these groups.

Early "help" , now "save the heart. "

"Xinmin Weekly" : You work in Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital, the main admission of critically ill patients, you see patients in the current state of mind?

Wang Zhen: Members of the mental health team who work at the designated intake hospital serve patients primarily in the form of liaison consultations, in other words, clinicians find that some patients may have psychological problems, they'll send us to a specialist for tests and diagnostics.

Yesterday we consulted three patients, one of whom was elderly and had already developed symptoms of depression, and the initial assessment was moderate depression.

The old man's wife died many years ago, before living alone, take care of themselves without much problem. After being admitted to Jinyintan Hospital, we were in charge of the Hubei Medical Team in Shanghai. He recovered quickly from the treatment, but his mental state has not been so good. When not cured, he often clamored to be discharged from the hospital, in fact, it is a manifestation of anxiety and fear. Now that he was well enough to leave the hospital, he was determined not to leave. The clinician said that when he was told to leave the hospital, he refused to speak to the doctor, was very upset and even had the idea of committing suicide.

We went into the hospital room to talk to him at the bedside. He wouldn't talk at first, but then he finally said it. His biggest fear was that he wouldn't be welcome home.

The old man is very eager to go home, but the children may tell him, for fear that he can not go back to life, everyone in isolation, the home is unable to take care of him.

He didn't want to leave because he was worried. Plus the hospital staff to take good care of him, this contrast, the heart will be very sad, feel oneself can not go home, slowly generate some negative thoughts.

Knowing what he was thinking, we started with some cognitive counseling, telling him that the community had a life plan for him in isolation after he left the hospital. Then guide him to understand his children's original intention is not to dislike him, teach him how to communicate with his children. And Guide him through his grief.

After nearly half an hour of psychological counseling, the old man's mood has calmed down, but because his depressive symptoms are still more obvious, we also gave him medication. We don't have the antidepressants we need, and just before you called me, I was coordinating a transfer to the hospital with the help of the Wuhan Mental Health Center.

Xinmin Weekly: The other two patients had less symptoms, right?

Wang Zhen: Yes. There was a middle-aged patient who had been cured of pneumonia and had been able to walk around the ward, doing well in every way. One day the doctor told him he could leave the hospital, and the next day he couldn't get out of bed. The clinician knew that he was a physical response to psychological symptoms, but did not know how to deal with them.

The patient said he was worried: What if I get sick again and there is no doctor to help me? What if I'm not really good? He felt safe in the hospital. It wasn't safe to go home.

We went in, we gave him some counseling, we gave him some relaxation exercises, and he's basically fine since we talked.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Three psychiatrists from Shanghai Mental Health Center are in Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital

Xinmin Weekly: We imagine that we would be very happy to be out of the hospital. I didn't know discharge patients were prone to mental health problems.

Wang Zhen: When the disease is serious, there is no time to take into account the psychological feelings, then life saving, and when the patient's physical disease eased, the psychological symptoms showed up. Our psychological medical team came to Wuhan more than a month after the outbreak. It was a good time. We hoped to help him ease his anxiety during the stress period when the epidemic was not over, so as not to cause long-term effects. Because the early main task is to save the patient, the psychologist in the "life-saving" section is not too much use, or even make trouble. In the middle and late stages of the epidemic, it is important for the National Health Commission to send out psychological medical teams in time.

Children and the elderly, the weak in the epidemic

Xinmin Weekly: What other psychological problems are unique among patients?

Wang Zhen: The hospital where several of my colleagues work in the Shanghai psychiatric team, has patients who have been transferred from nursing homes, some of whom have Alzheimer's disease, or early Alzheimer's disease.

Some of these patients can not not not cooperate with treatment, will multiply the workload of health care workers, may health care workers to take care of this patient, the other seven or eight patients can not cope. We received a consultation request, through drug treatment and part of the support of emotional counseling, to help patients better with the treatment. For example, for those with sleep reversal Alzheimer's who have behavioral disorders during the night, we can give a sedative that improves both behavior and sleep, says antipsychotic, MD, a sleep researcher at the University of California, San Diego.

Xinmin Weekly: What other groups do you think need special attention?

Wang Zhen: Son! This is a group that I think needs special attention. A team of colleagues from the Shanghai team worked at the Wuhan Children's Hospital, which treated some of the children. My biggest concern is their future.

Many of the cases were family-acquired. Some of these children may have lost their parents to the disease. Their psychological problems require our attention.

We're still running a screen, trying to get a ballpark figure on each kid. This screening is not easy to do, because some children may not know the family situation, adults and children in different places for treatment.

Xinmin Weekly: There have also been a lot of sad news stories recently, such as a child living with his grandfather, who had been dead for two or three days when a member of the community knocked on his door. There was another girl, chasing the hearse, calling out for her mother. These kids, are they GONNA be traumatized?

Wang Zhen: Yes. At present our work is still limited to medical institutions, Wuhan community because of the outbreak of direct psychological harm children, we can not take into account, hope that the community attention to them.

"Chronic Stress Response" of infectious disease epidemic situation is different from earthquake

Xinmin Weekly: We saw the square dancing in the shelter hospital. Is the mental health of the patients with mild illness better?

Wang Zhen: our Shanghai team of 50 doctors was divided into 10 teams, and we were assigned to 10 hospitals, six of which were designated hospitals, four of which were shelter hospitals, and each team had five doctors.

The situation in a shelter hospital is very different from that in a designated hospital. There are many people in the shelter hospital, many thousands of them. The common psychological problem of the patients in the shelter hospital is anxiety. The main cause of anxiety, apart from the disease itself, is the fear of uncertainty about the future. For example, they have to go into quarantine after going out of the cabin. They worry about the living arrangement there. They also worry about whether they will be discriminated against or ostracized when they return home.

Another common symptom is insomnia. On the one hand, the reason for insomnia is not adapted to the environment of the Shelter Hospital, on the other hand, there are also concerns about the epidemic, because the whole epidemic has not ended, psychological stress is still there. Depression is relatively rare in a shelter hospital, but if anxiety is not alleviated, the effects can be severe and depression can occur in some people over a long period of time.

Overall, about 50% of patients who actively express their emotional problems to health care professionals need some psychological intervention, but their psychological problems are relatively mild, we can take a variety of forms of intervention.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Fifty specialists from the Shanghai Mental Health Center and the Shanghai District Mental Health Center form the Shanghai Aid Hubei Medical Team

Xinmin Weekly: What psychological interventions are available to psychologists in a shelter hospital?

Wang Zhen: You can see the patients dancing in the square. In fact, after I came here, I also had some exchanges with the doctors on the front line. The doctors think that square dancing is not suitable for everyone, i wouldn't go dancing in a public square. Do breathing exercise is better, the amount of exercise is not large, and can adjust the breathing function, or the right amount of activities is better.

The overall mental health of the patients in the shelter hospital is relatively good, which has an important relationship with the overall coordination and management of the shelter hospital as well as logistical support in place. For example, the food supply for the patients is very good, but the more important reason is that the doctors and nurses involved in the shelter work are very professional and care for the patients, and the harmonious doctor-patient relationship helps to reduce the ill effects of the disease on the patients.

For patients who need psychological intervention, we have taken a variety of psychological intervention measures. For example, the Shelter Hospital has a broadcasting system, we are busy these two days recording a variety of audio programs to provide patients with some mental health knowledge, psychological protection.

Another important task is to conduct psychological screening of patients. The medical team, in cooperation with Shanghai Jiaotong University, built an assessment system. We put qr codes on our shelter hospitals, and on our doctor's protective clothing. Patients scan the codes and do self-help psychological assessments, the patient sees the results for himself and comes to the psychologist. Doctors in the background can also see the results of the survey, doctors if the situation is more serious patients, can take the initiative to contact patients for timely intervention. We'll know more about the patient when we have a lot of patient studies.

We have also done a lot of mental health information, ready to take to the shelter hospital to send to patients, but also use wechat tweets, so that patients understand more psychological knowledge and self-help methods.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In Wuhan, Wang Zhen held an online meeting with the Shanghai Jiaotong University research team to develop tools for psychological assessment and treatment of patients and health care workers affected by the outbreak

Xinmin Weekly: How are the psychological problems of patients in infectious disease epidemics different from disasters like earthquakes, fires and so on?

Wang Zhen: Infectious Diseases are not like earthquakes. Earthquakes and fires are one time things. Infectious Diseases last a long time, and a lot of people have psychological problems because of chronic stress.

Whether it's a fire or an earthquake, it's confined to a specific area. Even a quake as big as the Wenchuan County quake is only in Sichuan Province, and the rest of the country is unlikely to be affected. Infectious diseases are different, especially this one, which is spreading very fast, and everyone is potentially at risk, so it's very easy to create a panic in the whole society, even if you don't have an infected person around you, you're in a panic because you don't know if it's going to happen to you tomorrow.

A real threat can cause a dramatic rise in anxiety levels, which, unlike earthquakes and fires, do not affect the same number of people. In areas where the epidemic is severe, people like these in Wuhan may have post traumatic stress disorder, especially if they have a disease of their own that has a lingering effect, or if a family member has died, or those who have witnessed the death of a relative, or someone close to them, may develop the disease later.

But we also found that traditional Chinese culture has a strong protective effect on our mental health, so the rate of true PTSD later in life may be lower than reported in the West. In this kind of group crisis, Chinese people's psychological resilience seems to be stronger, for example, the traditional belief that "if you survive a disaster, you will be blessed later" has its very positive significance in the face of a big disaster, to protect our mental health.

Another must be emphasized is the strong response mechanisms adopted by our countries and governments, the strong mobilization and coordination capacity in the face of the epidemic, which can invisibly enhance people's confidence and sense of security.

Xinmin Weekly: Do you think the intervention of psychological intervention in the NCP epidemic is a big improvement over the past?

Wang Zhen: After the 2008 earthquake in Wenchuan County, there were a lot of psychologists and counselors who volunteered to work in the disaster area. Their wish is good, but because the psychological intervention work organization is quite chaotic, some people actually bring the disaster victims the second trauma. There are some psychological counselors lack of professional ability, to the scene will also bring some trouble.

After the Wenchuan County earthquake and other disasters, the field of psychological intervention to sum up the experience and lessons, now all aspects of the importance of psychological intervention, organizational capacity and professionalism than in those years much progress.

Xinmin Weekly: In these years of major disasters and infectious diseases, more and more psychologists are being seen. What are the results of your work?

Wang Zhen: In my memory, the first time Shanghai had a large scale psychological intervention was after the 1115 fire. Less than 24 hours after the fire, the psychological intervention team from the Shanghai Mental Health Center had already entered the scene. We did psychological screening and counseling for people who were affected by the disaster. It was a very successful psychological crisis intervention. These experiences for the follow-up of a variety of emergencies in the psychological intervention work, played a good role in the model. Later our psychological medical team also participated in the Bund stampede accident, many field explosion accident, shipwreck accident, etc. , the effect is better.

If the epidemic situation of infectious disease intervention, in 2003, when the Shanghai Mental Health Center Professor Xu Yifeng and Professor Huang Jizhong went to the treatment of SARS patients in the Shanghai Public Health Center work. In those days, there were no video phones, and unlike today, when everyone had a cell phone, doctors had to write instructions on cardboard through a window. It was our first official attempt at a psychological intervention. At the end of last year, when the plague struck Inner Mongolia, Shanghai also sent in psychologists.

After 2003, after several major events, the emergency system of psychological crisis intervention has been gradually established in China. With the development of society, Mental Health System, mental emergency mechanism gradually mature, a variety of plans gradually complete, once the outbreak, the emergency system on the start. As soon as the Wuhan epidemic broke out, the Shanghai Mental Health Center was already making preparations. Especially after we saw that a psychiatric hospital in Wuhan had infected medical staff, we were ready to take over some of the wards if necessary, but later our Wuhan colleague was very hard but brave to come through.

"Xinmin Weekly" : The psychological medical team to Wuhan also has a task is to ensure the psychological health of medical staff, at present you think the situation of medical staff?

Wang Zhen: these days we are in contact with more than the Shanghai Medical Team in Hubei Medical Staff, the overall situation is not bad, the more common problem is mainly insomnia.

There are several reasons for insomnia: First of all, many of our front-line nurses are senior and many of them are head nurses. They don't have to work shifts in their normal jobs. After arriving in Wuhan, they are scheduled according to ordinary nurses, difficulty adjusting your body clock can cause insomnia. In addition, the medical staff working in the ICU are under psychological and physical pressure. The patients are very sick. The medical staff often have to face such events as death due to ineffective treatment, which has a great impact on their psychology, this can cause mood swings, including anxiety, which is also an important cause of insomnia.

After we came here this time, we encountered some insomnia, anxiety of the medical staff, are doing the corresponding treatment. I think it will get better in the future, but if the treatment work lasts too long, homesickness is also a factor affecting the psychological state of the medical staff. Many of them have been in Wuhan for more than a month and are looking forward to going home. Moreover, on the one hand, we want to go home, want to rest, on the one hand, our medical staff are very dedicated, is very active to come to Wuhan to participate in the treatment, they also want to do the immediate work well, then there will be internal contradictions and conflicts.

Although I am cautiously optimistic, I am also worried that some medical staff are not willing to speak their minds, afraid that others will think that they are vulnerable, afraid of being misunderstood by others, so I will do more detailed work next, screen for those who don't reveal their true thoughts and emotions.
